poem:
Underpass Echolalia

Brum was the underpass; the puddles glimmed and murgled low,
The railings hummed in twingle-chords; the driplights cindered slow;
The scrawl and scrag of graffijags made shimmers on the skin,
And echo-bells went rimble-run along the hollow din.

“Mind you the Cavoox, spraddled sprig—the backtalk beast of tone!
It gulps your shout and gifts it back, but razored, not your own;
Beware the mumble-murmurhounds; sidestep the Yonderflume—
For underspan is trickle-trap and spool of guttergloom.”

I took my hush-hook, silverstrung, my reson-tempered cane;
Long time I sought a gaggle-nook beside the tramline’s lane;
I nested by a pillar-post, with sandwich, sip, and crust,
And whistled out a suttle air to stir the sleeping dust.

While I dilly-mused and munched, the Cavoox oozled gray,
Its double-mouth all overmouth, its feelers spooled of say;
It mirrored back my whistled whim, then bent it wicked-wry—
A ping turned into knifeling clang, a coo to clatter-cry.

I sprang! The hush-hook looped and rang—ker-rindle, rindle-rang!
We scrabbled through the pillar-fog with snag and snagging tang;
A twist, a flisk, a counterflisk—its earlids snapped in two—
I netted up its feedback-heart and fed it back anew.

The Cavoox shrank to thimble-size; its bellow blurred to mote,
The underpass unknotted then; a calm uncurled my throat;
The puddles smoothed like button-glass; the railings purred as one,
And hush came down in velvet folds where rumble used to run.

Ripple-bright, the morning spilled beyond the culvert’s rim;
They cheered at home: “You quieted the underpass’s hymn!
You nixed the Cavoox, dread of din, and all its dither-din!”
Now footfalls bloom in gentle loops and wander inward, thin.

Still brum the arches, mild and moot; the graffijags lie still;
The twingle fades to single tone along the tunnel’s chill;
Keep close your hush-hook, spraddled sprig—walk soft and carry song,
For echoes love to borrow words and send them back along.
